715981f.text:
Amsterdam Avenue, at the N. E. corner of Cathedral Parkway (W. 110th Street) showing constructionsl details of the Protestant Episcopal Cathedral of St. John, the cornerstorne of which was laid on St. John's Day, December 17, 1892 by Bishop Potter. TRe plans are by Heins and La Farge. TRis site was formerly occupied
by the Leake and Watts Orphan Asylum.
About 1910
Ewing Galloway

715972f-a.text:
Amsterdam Ave., east side, south from Cathedral Parkway (left) to WTest 109th Street (right) showing the Womans Hospital on the left, facing on the south side of the Parkway. The glazed skylighted structure shown, is the Art School of the National Academy of Design is located at the N.E. corner of the Avenue and West 109th Street. N 2 of this set is in a northeastward direction to show the latter prominently. In addition one sees an extensive view eastward on the
side of 109th Street.
November 7, 1937.
P. L. Sperr.

715973f-a.text:
Amsterdam Avenue, at the N. E. corner of Cathedral Parkway (West 110th Street), showing the Leake : Watts Orphan Asylum. Incorporated in 1831 by John G. Leake and Bobert Watts; the buildings here were erected in 1843 at 113th Street. After the sale of the site to the Protestant Episcopal Archdioscese for the site of St. John's Cathedral in 1886, they moved to Ludlow. For further details, see, Kings Handbook of New York
(1893), page 430.
1892
H. N. Tiemann, photo
Gift of Urbrock Collection
